data.content:
**Yes, C# fully supports `stackalloc`'d `Span<nint>` and `Span<nuint>`.** Both work without issues:

```csharp
Span<nint>  values   = stackalloc nint[] { 1, 2, 3, 4, 5 };
Span<nuint> unsigned = stackalloc nuint[3];
```

The test ran successfully on .NET 11, producing correct results (sum of 1–5 = 15, element size = 8 bytes on this 64-bit system). This has been supported since C# 9 / .NET 5 when `nint`/`nuint` were introduced as first-class types — they're valid `unmanaged` types, which is the constraint for `stackalloc`.
